:"na 1278","1170":"1170","Kerry, Powys, Wales, United Kingdom":"Kerry, Powys, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ceri, Ceri, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Kerry, Montgomeryshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kerry, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Kerry, Montgomeryshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1200–AFT    1278":"1200–after 1278","1200–1278":"1200–1278","1210–Male":"1210–Deceased","1220–Female":"1220–Deceased","1234–Female":"1234–Deceased","1268–Male":"1268–Deceased","1277–Male":"1277–Deceased","1165–1250":"1165–1250","1170–Female":"1170–Deceased","1268":"1268","Abt 1277":"about 1277","1234":"1234","1278":"1278","1200":"1200","1277":"1277","1210":"1210","1165":"1165","1220":"1220","1250":"1250","AFT    1278":"after 1278","1170":"1170","Kerry, Powys, Wales, United Kingdom":"Kerry, Powys, Wales, United Kingdom","Ceri, Ceri, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Kerry, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Kerry, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Kerry, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Madog","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name, possibly having the sense ‘fortunate’ or alternatively from Celtic <i>aodh</i> ‘fire’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Kerry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Australian origin, a modern coinage, probably from the name of the Irish county. It is also quite common in Britain and elsewhere in the English-speaking world, especially as a girl's name."],"variants":[{"name":"Kerrie","meanings":["Of Australian origin, a modern coinage, probably from the name of the Irish county. It is also quite common in Britain and elsewhere in the English-speaking world, especially as a girl's name."]},{"name":"Kerri","meanings":["Of Australian origin, a modern coinage, probably from the name of the Irish county. It is also quite common in Britain and elsewhere in the English-speaking world, especially as a girl's name."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Madog ap Maredudd of Kerry was born in 1200, in Kerry, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Prince Maredudd Ap Maelgwn, was 35 and his mother, Anne Ap Maelgwn born Scudamore, was 30. He had at least 2 sons with Mrs. Madog ap Maredudd. He died after 1278."},"et":{"1200–AFT    1278":"1200–pärast 1278","1200–1278":"1200–1278","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1220–Female":"1220–Surnud","1234–Female":"1234–Surnud","1268–Male":"1268–Surnud","1277–Male":"1277–Surnud","1165–1250":"1165–1250","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1268":"1268","Abt 1277":"umbes 1277","1234":"1234","1278":"1278","1200":"1200","1277":"1277","1210":"1210","1165":"1165","1220":"1220","1250":"1250","AFT    1278":"pärast 1278","1170":"1170","Kerry, Powys, Wales, United Kingdom":"Kerry, Powys, Wales, United Kingdom","Ceri, Ceri, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Kerry, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Kerry, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Kerry, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1200–AFT    1278":"1200–1278 jälkeen","1200–1278":"1200–1278","1210–Male":"1210–Kuollut","1220–Female":"1220–Kuollut","1234–Female":"1234–Kuollut","1268–Male":"1268–Kuollut","1277–Male":"1277–Kuollut","1165–1250":"1165–1250","1170–Female":"1170–Kuollut","1268":"1268","Abt 1277":"noin 1277","1234":"1234","1278":"1278","1200":"1200","1277":"1277","1210":"1210","1165":"1165","1220":"1220","1250":"1250","AFT    1278":"1278 jälkeen","1170":"1170","Kerry, Powys, Wales, United Kingdom":"Kerry, Powys, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Ceri, Ceri, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Kerry, Montgomeryshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kerry, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Kerry, Montgomeryshire, Wales